definitions.definition: The amount of money taken as sales transacted in a given period.
examples: The company had an annual turnover of $500,000.

definitions.definition: The frequency with which stock is replaced after being used or sold, workers leave and are replaced, a property changes hands, etc.
examples: High staff- turnover can lead to low morale amongst employees
Those apartments have a high turnover because they are so close to the railroad tracks.

definitions.definition: A semicircular pastry made by turning one half of a circular crust over the other, enclosing the filling (such as fruit).
examples: They only served me one apple turnover for breakfast.

definitions.definition: A loss of possession of the ball without scoring.
examples: The Nimrods committed another dismaying turnover en route to another humiliating loss.

definitions.definition: A measure of leg speed: the frequency with which one takes strides when running, typically given in strides per minute.
The act or result of overturning something; an upset .
An apprentice , in any trade, who is handed over from one master to another to complete his time.
